Part I - Data Exploration of NYC's Citi Bike Sharing System (2022)¶

by Sulaiman Handu¶

Introduction¶

Citi bike is a privately owned bicycle sharing system serving the New York City and New Jersey. The company has been acquired by Lyft and uses technologies by Lyft in its stations and operations. Named after lead sponsor Citigroup, It officially opened in May 2013 with 332 stations and 6,000 bikes. By October 2017 annual expansions brought the totals to 706 stations and 12,000 bikes, making the service the largest bike sharing program in the United States.

Gathering and Importing Data.¶

Lyft operates New York City’s Citi Bike bicycle sharing service and is committed to supporting bicycling as an alternative transportation option. As part of that commitment, Lyft makes certain Citi Bike system data available to the public. Published downloadable files of the Citi bike trip data are made available here. The scope of study is to analyse 2022 bike sharing data. Files containing data for each of the months in that year have been dowloaded. Data of each month will be merged to form a complete and single dataset for the year 2022.

Cleaning¶

To make the data tidy and ready for use the following issues will have to be resolved:

  1. Remove all null values
  2. replace the dot "." in the start station and end station ids.
  3. Change the data format to date time type
  4. identify the categorical column and change their data type.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset originally 13 columns and over 30 million rows

  • Ride ID: The unique Identifier of each ride
  • Rideable type: The type of bike
  • Started at: Time the ride started
  • Ended at : Time the ride ended
  • Start station name: The station the ride started
  • Start station ID: The start station the ride ID
  • End station name: The station the ride ended
  • End station ID: The end station ID
  • Start latitude
  • Start longitude
  • End latitude
  • End Longitude
  • Member or casual ride Additionally, columns were created from the above data to enable easy extraction of insights.
  • hr_started: The hour of the day the trip was started
  • dow_started: The day of the week ride was taken
  • month: The month of the ride
  • duration_sec: Time interval of bike sharing in seconds
  • duration_minute: Time interval of bike sharing in minutess

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features to explored in the dataset are:

  • The time of the day, week, month that bikes are mostly used.
  • what type of bike do riders prefer.
  • Which stations have the highest patronage.
  • Membership preference for ride type and timing.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features that will aid this exploration are hr_started, dow_started, month, duration_minute, member_casual, rideable_type.

Certain Attribute of interest will be examined in our dataset. Questions will be asked and attributes will be visualised to know how values are distributed within the dataset. Both the categorical and numenic data wil be observed to understand bikers behaviour and preferences.

What type of ride is most prefered by riders¶

In [72]:
def countplot(feature, sequence):
    if sequence == None:
        base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
        sb.countplot(data=df, x= feature, color = base_color)
    else:
        base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
        sb.countplot(data=df, x= feature, color = base_color, order = sequence )

Transformation 1¶

The distribution shows that we have negative values of duration. This is most likely due to error during entry. lets remove the negative duration from our dataset.

Transformation 2¶

Nearly all the rides were taken for less than 150 minutes in duration. we will focus mainly on rides within this boundary.

In [33]:
# Remove all ride with duration above 150 minutes
excess_min = df[df.duration_minute > 150]
df.drop(excess_min.index, inplace = True)

The Initial asssesment of the distribution in duration shows that we had some outliers and some incorrect values. Appropriate manipulation has been done to clear all irregularities. The duration of ride in the study was not greater than 150 minutes (2hrs, 30mins). Most cycling duration was actually less than 20 minutes. This is likely due to speed of cycling and consideration for close proximity.

What are the Most Popular and the Least Popular Stations.¶

These will be examined by checking the start and end end point. it is possible that some station are present in residential areas and thus will be starting point to most occupants. Commercial areas will mostly have workers approaching stations within that area as destination. Lets look into the data to find out more.

Conclusions¶

Exploration of the 2022 data has uncovered a lot of information about citi bike sharing system. The majority of its patronage comes from annual subscribers making up 78% of its total use for the year. Most of the cyclers prefer using classic bikes to electric bikes and only the casual cyclers ride the docked bike.

The cycling activities generally increases during the summer time. The summer time has also been the time when the cyclers ride the bikes for more time duration. There are lesser cycling activities in winter and people who ride bikes at this time are riding for a short period. Casual rider usually patronize more during the weekend. The annual subscribers on the other hand usually patronize more during the weekdays especially on Wednesdays to Friday.

During the day, cycling activities begin to increase as early as 5am and continues to increase until 3pm when it starts to decrease again.

More focus could be placed in areas were stations have the most cyclers staring and ending their rides. Visualisation actually shows the most popular stations are the places where rides are being started and ended with W21 St and 6 Ave being the most popular of all. More strategic decisions could be taken in areas that are less popular e.g Marketing.
